<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="166" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,324,265,291]" box="[189,324,265,291]" pageId="3" pageNumber="166">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,265,291]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="3" pageNumber="166" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,265,291]" pageId="3" pageNumber="166">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,1398,313,376]" pageId="3" pageNumber="166">
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[747,868,314,339]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="166">erromerus</emphasis>
, referring to the stout aedeagus of the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
